e living the best version of yourself, you inspire others to live the best versions of themselves.\n\n- Steve Maraboli, Unapologetically You: Reflections on Life and the Human Experience\n|\nThen you are a poet?' she asked, fingering the flyer in her pocket.'No not at all,' he waved his hand. 'I am merely a character in a poem.\n\n- Karen Tei Yamashita, Tropic of Orange\n|\nThere is no real aloneness. There is solitude and the nurturing silence that is relationship with ourselves, but even then we are part of something larger.\n\n- Linda Hogan, Dwellings: A Spiritual History of the Living World\n|\nBut I'm going to try to tell the truth. Except for the parts I'm leav­ing out, because there's still stuff I'm just not going to tell you. Get used to it.\n\n- Robin McKinley, Dragonhaven\n|\nYou see, the strangeness of my case is that now I no longer fear the invisible, I’m terrified by reality.\n\n- Jean\n|\nIn a society of thinking humanity, it should always be, humans first, and then Gods, Krishna or otherwise.\n\n- Abhijit Naskar, The Krishna Cancer\n|\nA candle, a book and a peaceful person mean three candles for the world!\n\n- Mehmet\n|\nWhen I am alone in the forest at night-time and jump from one tree to another, I often think that life is so strange.\n\n- George Mikes, How to Be an Alien: A Handbook for Beginners and Advanced Pupils\n|\nWhen a complex is acquired, personal development is stopped and the person even being an adult, sometimes behaves in a childish and immature way\n\n- Sunday\n|\nI felt like one of Apollo's sacred cows- slow, dumb, and bright red.\n\n- Rick Riordan, The Last Olympian\n|\nSuccess is a way of life with the sense of connection, compassion, and expansion of human life.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nBut I can hardly sit still. I keep fidgeting, crossing one leg and then the other. I feel like I could throw off sparks, or break a window--maybe rearrange all the furniture.\n\n- Raymond Carver, Where I'm Calling From: New and Selected Stories\n|\nNow you’re listening to Swedish ?” I asked her. “He thinks I’m the Compass because every time I see ticktocks, I happen to be there!\n\n- Joel N. Ross, The Lost Compass\n|\nNothing is easier than to get peaceful people to renounce violence, even when they provide no concrete ways to prevent violence from others.\n\n- Thomas Sowell, Intellectuals and Society\n|\nI drink from a small spring, my thirst exceeds the ocean.\n\n- Adam Zagajewski, Without End: New and Selected Poems\n|\nTake away health, wealth, and material success and all you have is each other. Maybe that's the place we should start.\n\n- Charles Herrick, Breath of Kenya: A Missionary Journal\n|\nOne that society can't forgive, but I can.\n\n- Dennis Lehane, Shutter Island\n|\nThe Buddha is like space, with no inherent nature; appearing in the world to benefit the living, his features and refinements are like reflections.\n\n- Thomas Cleary, Flower Ornament Scripture: Translation of the Avatamsaka Sutra: v. 1\n|\nIf you can dance like raindrops, there will always be sunshine.\n\n- Curtis\n|\nThe American war is over, but this is far from being the case with the American Revolution.\n\n- Benjamin\n|\nWhen you have knowledge, patience, and passion, and pair those with hard work, you will find success -- but don’t ever forget about kindness.\n\n- Adam\n|\nIf you think only sunshine brings you happiness, then you have not danced in the rain\n\n- Unknown\n|\nTruth, like love and sleep, resents approaches that are too intense.\n\n- W.H.\n|\nIt is always, first Self, then everything else.\n\n- Abhijit Naskar, Principia Humanitas\n|\nDreams are not those which comes while we are sleeping, but dreams are those when u don't sleep before fulfilling them.\n\n- A.P.J. Abdul Kalam, Wings of Fire: An Autobiography\n|\nI don't have any special talents, just an ordinary desire to live like a human being.\n\n- Mikhail Bulgakov, The Master and Margarita\n|\nThe more completely you can be yourself, the more fully and consciou